<font color="#FF0000">ARE MEDALS FOR VALOR VALIANT?</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 24 17:27:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hey Prophet, welcome to the group. May I suggest that you<br>
read previous posts on #6 Viet Nam Protests as well as this site #44.  I have had my own &quot;metamorphisis&quot; so to speak, actually I sounded a like like you do now.  I have grown and learned from others here, and from reading what was said before I stuck my big 2 cents in.  May I suggest the same?  Go back and read prior comments before you get angry and attack. <br><br>
I have no issue, nor anger with the medals of war. I pose a rhetorical question, if not a question of ethics.  We all agree the war was wrong, the gov't lied, and mislead all of us.  Yes a medal for bravery for saving one's comrades is a wonderful thing (i.e. the guy who jumps on top of the granade and give his life for his buddies), that is personal bravery and awesome.  <br><br>
The ethical question is (and I know Doc Del has heard this before-sorry Brian for the headache), is a medal given for wiping out a machine gun nest a wonderful thing if those in the nest are just defending their country, and we are the invader??  Bravery towards one fellows, damn yes, wear it with pride. Medals for killing peasants who had no choice, REPEAT-NO CHOICE, their country had been invaded (by us), is that a medal of the same valor (pardon the pun)?<br><br>
I don't wear my C.O.Status, or what I USED TO think was my Moral Highground, but I don't hate those who fled to Canada anymore than those sucked into Nam.  What is it that you want to prove?  That is the real question I distill between your words and your anger?  Consider it.  We all here share our thoughts, and feelings, quite openly, for better or worse, higher or lower ground.  <br><br>
doc<br><br>

